    body: `<p>Before you spend months trying to land a sales agent, it's worth asking an honest question that the industry rarely puts plainly: <strong>does your film actually need one — and can it realistically get one?</strong> The default assumption in international sales is that you should have a sales agent, and for many films that's right. But a sales agent isn't automatic, isn't free (they take a commission), and isn't attainable for every film. Reputable agents are selective, taking on films they believe have international appeal they can actually sell. So the real question has two halves: <em>would</em> a sales agent add enough value to be worth the commission, and <em>could</em> you plausibly land a good one given your film's appeal and profile. Answering both honestly — before you pour effort into the chase — tells you whether to pursue a sales agent hard, pursue international sales in some lighter form, or focus your energy on the domestic and DIY channels you already understand. This chapter is that honest assessment, closing out the foundations before we get practical about finding an agent.</p>

<h2>When a sales agent makes sense — and when it doesn't</h2>

<p>Weigh these factors honestly:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Does your film travel?</b> Genre films, festival films with prestige, and docs on global-interest subjects tend to have international appeal a sales agent can sell. Hyper-local films often don't.</li>
  <li><b>Is there enough value to share?</b> A sales agent takes a commission; if your film's realistic international revenue is small, the commission may leave little — though an agent may still reach sales you couldn't alone.</li>
  <li><b>Can you attract a reputable agent?</b> Good agents are selective. A strong festival run, a recognizable genre hook, or notable talent helps; without any of that, landing a good agent is hard.</li>
  <li><b>Do you have the relationships yourself?</b> Almost no independent filmmaker does — which is the core argument for a sales agent, since they supply the buyer relationships you lack.</li>
  <li><b>What's your alternative?</b> Some films do better focusing on domestic release, DIY, and a few direct international opportunities than chasing a full international-sales campaign.</li>
  <li><b>Beware bad agents.</b> A weak or predatory agent can be worse than none — tying up your rights while delivering little. Sometimes no agent beats the wrong one.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Making the honest call</h2>

<p>The way to decide is to be <strong>ruthlessly honest about your film's international appeal and profile, rather than optimistic.</strong> Start with the film itself: does it have the kind of appeal that travels? A horror film, a high-concept thriller, an action film, a visually distinctive festival film, or a documentary on a subject people care about worldwide — these travel, and a sales agent has real material to sell. A talky, culturally specific drama with no recognizable talent and no festival pedigree is much harder to sell internationally, and an agent may pass or, if they take it, may sell little. Being honest here saves you from a demoralizing chase for something that isn't there. Then weigh the economics and the alternative: a sales agent's commission is worth paying if it unlocks sales you couldn't reach yourself (which, given that you have no international buyer relationships, it usually would) — but only if there are sales to unlock. If your film's realistic international potential is genuinely small, you might be better served focusing your limited energy on the domestic and DIY channels you understand, and treating any international sale as a bonus rather than a campaign. A few honest cautions. First, <em>landing a good agent is itself a hurdle</em> — because reputable agents are selective, "needing" one and "getting" one are different things, and part of this assessment is realistically judging whether your film can attract a good agent at all (the next chapter is about how to try). Second, <em>the wrong agent can be worse than none</em> — an agent who ties up your worldwide rights for years but doesn't actively sell, or who has poor accounting practices, can leave you worse off than if you'd kept the rights and pursued a few sales yourself, which is why the choosing chapter matters as much as the finding chapter. Third, <em>this isn't all-or-nothing</em> — even without a traditional sales agent, some international revenue may be reachable through certain platforms, aggregators, or direct opportunities, so "no sales agent" doesn't have to mean "no international sales," just a different, usually smaller-scale approach. Fourth, <em>the honest answer might be "not yet"</em> — if your film hasn't had the festival run or profile that would attract a good agent, the move may be to build that profile first (through the festival strategy you've studied) and revisit international sales once your film has the credentials agents respond to. If, after this honest assessment, your film has international appeal and could plausibly attract a reputable agent, then pursuing one is very likely worth it — that's what the rest of this course helps you do. If not, you've saved yourself a frustrating chase and can direct your energy where it'll actually pay off. Either way, you're deciding with clear eyes. Next, Module 2 gets practical: how to actually find and land a sales agent.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The question has two halves: would a sales agent add enough value to be worth the commission, and could you realistically land a good one? Answer both honestly before the chase — it tells you where to put your energy.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I've watched two filmmakers make opposite calls, both correctly. One had a genre film with a strong festival buzz — clearly a travel-ready film — and chased a sales agent hard; it paid off across many territories. The other had a deeply personal, culturally specific drama, assessed honestly that it wouldn't travel far, skipped the international-sales campaign, and poured everything into a focused domestic and DIY release that suited the film. The lesson wasn't "always get an agent" or "never bother." It was: look at your actual film, judge honestly whether it travels and whether you could land a good agent, and decide from there — not from wishful thinking.</p>
</div>`,
