    body: `<p>If you've decided your film is a candidate for international sales, the practical challenge is landing a sales agent — and it helps enormously to understand that <strong>this isn't a cold-application process so much as a matchmaking one.</strong> Sales agents aren't waiting for submissions the way festivals are; they're actively looking for films that fit their slate, mostly at festivals and through industry relationships, and they say yes to films they believe they can sell into enough territories to make it worth their while. So "finding an agent" is really about two things: putting your film where agents look (which is largely festivals), and identifying the specific agents whose slate your film fits, then approaching them the right way. Done well, this turns a vague and intimidating hunt into a targeted process. This chapter walks through where agents find films, what makes them commit, and how to approach them — the practical heart of Module 2.</p>

<h2>Where agents look and what makes them say yes</h2>

<p>The realities of the search:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Festivals are the main venue.</b> Agents scout films at festivals — a strong festival premiere or run is the most common way a film gets on an agent's radar.</li>
  <li><b>Fit matters more than quality alone.</b> Agents specialize — some in genre, some in arthouse, some in docs. Target agents whose slate matches your film, not just any agent.</li>
  <li><b>They assess sellability.</b> Agents commit to films they believe they can sell into enough territories — appeal, hook, cast, and festival pedigree all feed that judgment.</li>
  <li><b>Research the field.</b> Look at which agents represented films like yours (festival and market credits are public) to build a targeted shortlist.</li>
  <li><b>Warm intros help.</b> An introduction from a producer, festival programmer, or industry contact carries far more weight than a cold approach.</li>
  <li><b>Materials must be ready.</b> A finished (or near-finished) film, a strong trailer, and clean rights let an agent act — being ready when interest strikes matters.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Approaching agents the right way</h2>

<p>The most reliable path to a sales agent runs through <strong>festivals and targeted, well-researched outreach rather than mass cold submissions.</strong> Start by getting your film in front of agents where they actually look, which mostly means festivals — a strong festival premiere or run is the classic way films get discovered by agents, who attend to scout for their slates (this is one more reason the festival strategy you've studied matters so much). Alongside that, do your homework: research which agents represent films like yours by looking at festival and market credits, and build a shortlist of agents whose slate and specialty genuinely fit your film, because a genre-focused agent is the right target for a genre film and the wrong one for an arthouse drama. Then approach them well — ideally through a warm introduction from a producer, programmer, or industry contact, which carries far more weight than a cold email, but if you must go direct, make it targeted and professional: a concise note about why your specific film fits their specific slate, with a link to the film or a strong trailer and the key selling points (festival selections, cast, hook) up front. A few honest points about the process. First, <em>timing is everything</em> — the best moment to attract an agent is around a strong festival premiere, when your film has buzz and credentials, so coordinating your festival strategy with your search for an agent (rather than treating them as separate) markedly improves your odds. Second, <em>be ready before you're wanted</em> — an agent who's interested wants to be able to act, so having a finished or near-finished film, a compelling trailer, and clean, unencumbered rights means you can say yes when they say yes, rather than scrambling. Third, <em>fit beats prestige</em> — the biggest, most prestigious agent isn't necessarily right for your film; an agent who specializes in exactly your kind of film and will actually prioritize it often serves you better than a large agency where your small film sits at the bottom of the slate (a theme the choosing chapter develops). Fourth, <em>rejection is normal and not personal</em> — agents pass on films constantly for reasons of fit, slate capacity, and market conditions that have nothing to do with your film's worth, so a "no" from one agent simply means moving to the next targeted candidate, not that international sales are off the table. Landing a sales agent is a real hurdle, but it's a navigable one when you approach it as targeted matchmaking: put your film where agents look (festivals), identify the agents your film genuinely fits, get in front of them well (ideally warm), and be ready to move when interest strikes. Do that, and you give your film its best shot at representation. Next, once an agent is interested, we look at the deal itself — commission, terms, and what you're actually agreeing to.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Finding an agent is matchmaking, not cold applications. Put your film where agents look — festivals — target the specific agents your film fits, approach them warmly, and be ready to move when interest strikes.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first attempt at landing an agent was a spreadsheet of fifty companies and a copy-pasted email blast. Near-zero response. The film that actually got repped went a completely different way: it premiered at a festival, a specific agent who handled exactly that kind of film saw it in the room, and a producer friend made a warm introduction the next morning. One targeted, well-timed, warm connection did what fifty cold emails couldn't. I stopped thinking of it as applying to agents and started thinking of it as getting my film in front of the right one at the right moment.</p>
</div>`,
