    body: `<p>There's a place where international sales actually happen, and it's worth understanding even though your sales agent, not you, will be the one working it: the <strong>film market.</strong> A film market is an industry event — often attached to a major festival — where sellers (sales agents) and buyers (distributors from around the world) gather to trade films. Deals that license your film into territory after territory are largely made here, in booths and screening rooms and meetings, over the few intense days a market runs. This is where the abstract idea of "selling territory by territory" becomes a physical reality: your sales agent sets up at the market, screens your film for buyers, takes meetings with the distributor from each territory, and closes deals in person. Understanding the market matters even if you never attend one yourself, because it explains why a sales agent's market presence is so valuable, why the festival-and-market calendar shapes the timing of your international sales, and what your agent is actually doing on your film's behalf. This chapter is about that engine room of international sales.</p>

<h2>How markets work</h2>

<p>The mechanics of selling at a market:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Markets pair with festivals.</b> Major film markets often run alongside major festivals — the festival creates buzz and the market is where that buzz turns into deals.</li>
  <li><b>Sellers and buyers gather.</b> Sales agents (sellers) and distributors from every territory (buyers) converge for a few days of concentrated dealmaking.</li>
  <li><b>Your agent represents you there.</b> The sales agent sets up, screens your film, and takes buyer meetings on your behalf — you generally don't attend as a filmmaker.</li>
  <li><b>Screenings drive interest.</b> Market screenings let buyers assess your film; a strong screening or festival reception generates the buyer interest that leads to deals.</li>
  <li><b>Deals close territory by territory.</b> Buyers acquire your film for their territory; a good market can produce multiple territory deals in a short span.</li>
  <li><b>Timing follows the calendar.</b> The market calendar shapes when your film sells — agents plan launches around key markets to maximize buyer attention.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Why the market matters to you</h2>

<p>Even though the market is your sales agent's arena rather than yours, understanding it changes how you think about your whole international-sales strategy, because <strong>the market is where your agent's relationships, your film's festival buzz, and the timing of your release all come together to produce actual deals.</strong> It clarifies why a sales agent's market presence is worth so much: they're not just emailing buyers from an office; they're physically in the room at the market, meeting the distributor from each territory, screening your film, and closing deals face to face over a few concentrated days — access and presence you couldn't replicate alone. It clarifies why the festival-and-market calendar shapes your timing: your agent will often plan your film's market launch to coincide with a strong festival moment, because a film arriving at a market with festival buzz commands far more buyer attention than one arriving cold, which is one more reason your festival strategy and your international-sales strategy are deeply linked. And it clarifies what your agent is actually doing for their commission — the market is a lot of work, and a good agent's preparation, relationships, and salesmanship there directly determine how many territories your film sells into. A few honest points. First, <em>you usually won't attend the market as a filmmaker</em> — markets are for sellers and buyers, and your sales agent represents you, so your job is to give your agent what they need to sell (a great film, strong materials, buzz) rather than to work the market floor yourself. Second, <em>buzz is the currency</em> — buyers at a market pay attention to films with momentum, so a strong festival premiere, good reviews, or awards attention translates directly into market interest, which is why the profile-building work of your festival run pays off precisely here. Third, <em>markets have rhythms and hierarchies</em> — some markets are bigger and more important than others, and your agent chooses which market and which moment to launch your film based on where its buyers are and when interest will peak, a strategic judgment that's part of what you're paying them for. Fourth, <em>a quiet market isn't necessarily failure</em> — not every film sells into many territories, and market conditions, competition, and timing all affect results, so honest expectations and a good agent's read of the market matter more than a single event's outcome. You may never set foot in a film market, but understanding it demystifies the whole business: it's where your agent turns your film's appeal and buzz into territory deals, where the calendar and the festival run come together, and where the commission you pay does its work. Next, we go deeper into the territories themselves — how foreign sales play out market by market.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The market is the engine room of international sales — where your agent's relationships, your film's festival buzz, and the timing of your release come together to produce actual territory deals. You may never attend one, but understanding it demystifies the whole business.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I didn't attend the market where my film sold — my agent did. But they sent me a debrief afterward, and reading it was an education. My film had screened for buyers on the back of a strong festival premiere, and because it arrived with buzz, the room paid attention. Over a handful of days, my agent had taken meetings with distributors from a dozen territories and closed deals with several. None of that would have happened from my laptop. That debrief taught me what I was actually paying an agent for: not emails, but presence in the one room where the whole world's buyers show up at once.</p>
</div>`,
