    body: `<p>Having covered the sales agent, the deal, and the market, this chapter closes Module 2 by looking at how foreign sales actually land — because the reality is <strong>a patchwork, not a clean sweep.</strong> Your film won't sell into every territory, and the territories it does sell into won't pay equally: some buy and some pass, some pay well and most pay modestly, and the pattern reflects your film's particular appeal in each market. A foreign film sales agent works this patchwork territory by territory — closing a strong deal in one market, a small one in another, and getting no interest in a third — and the sum of those varied outcomes is your foreign-sales revenue. Understanding that foreign sales are inherently uneven and patchwork, rather than a uniform payout, is essential for setting honest expectations and for reading your sales results without either false disappointment or false hope. This chapter is about how territories actually pay out and how to interpret what you get.</p>

<h2>How foreign sales actually land</h2>

<p>The realities of territory results:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Not every territory buys.</b> Your film sells into some territories and not others, depending on its appeal in each market — a patchwork, not a full map.</li>
  <li><b>Territories pay unequally.</b> Larger, wealthier markets typically pay more; many territories pay modestly. Revenue weights toward a few, with a long tail.</li>
  <li><b>Genre and appeal drive fit.</b> A film's genre and content determine which territories want it — some markets favor certain genres more than others.</li>
  <li><b>Deals come in over time.</b> Sales don't all close at once; they accumulate across markets and months as your agent works territory by territory.</li>
  <li><b>Some territories go unsold.</b> Unsold territories keep their rights with you, available for future sales as long as the agreement allows.</li>
  <li><b>The total is what matters.</b> Judge foreign sales by the accumulated total across territories, not by any single deal — the sum is the story.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Reading your foreign-sales results</h2>

<p>The key to interpreting foreign sales is to <strong>expect and accept unevenness, and to judge results by the accumulated total rather than any single territory.</strong> When your sales agent reports back, you'll see a patchwork: a solid deal in one significant market, modest deals in several others, small ones in a few more, and silence from territories that didn't bite. This is normal — foreign sales are inherently uneven because your film's appeal varies by market, and no film sells everywhere or pays equally. The mistake is to fixate on individual lines (disappointment at a small deal, or at a territory that passed) instead of looking at the whole column. Add up the varied outcomes across all the territories that did buy, and that sum — often meaningful even when no single deal was large — is your foreign-sales revenue and the real measure of the campaign. This framing also helps you understand <em>why</em> results look the way they do: a genre film may sell strongly into territories that favor that genre and weakly elsewhere; a festival film may sell into arthouse-friendly markets and pass in others; a film's particular content, cast, and appeal shape which parts of the world want it. A few honest points. First, <em>patience matters</em> — foreign sales accumulate over time as your agent works successive markets, so a film's international total builds over months (or longer), and an early quiet stretch doesn't mean the campaign has failed. Second, <em>unsold isn't lost</em> — territories that don't sell keep their rights with you (per your agreement), so they remain available for future sales, and a territory that passes today may buy later as circumstances change. Third, <em>the tail has value</em> — while revenue weights toward a few larger markets, the long tail of small territory deals adds up, and a patient agent who keeps selling into smaller markets can meaningfully grow your total beyond the headline deals. Fourth, <em>results reflect the film, honestly read</em> — the pattern of which territories bought and at what level is real information about your film's international appeal, useful for setting expectations on future projects and for understanding where your work travels. Foreign sales are a patchwork by nature: uneven across territories, weighted toward a few markets, accumulating over time, with some territories unsold and available. Reading them well means expecting that unevenness, judging by the accumulated total rather than any single deal, and understanding the pattern as honest information about where your film travels. With Module 2 complete, Module 3 turns to putting all of this to work — starting with the specific worlds of documentary and niche international sales.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Foreign sales are a patchwork, not a clean sweep — some territories buy, some pass, a few pay well and most pay modestly. Judge the campaign by the accumulated total across all territories, not by any single line.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>When my agent sent the first round of foreign-sales results, I nearly missed the point. One line was a decent deal; most were small; several strong-looking territories had passed entirely. My gut reaction was disappointment. Then a producer told me to stop reading lines and add the column. The total was real money — built from a patchwork of one solid deal, a handful of modest ones, and a long tail of small ones, from markets that happened to want my kind of film. Territories that passed weren't failures; some sold later. I learned to read foreign sales as a sum, accumulating over time, not as a verdict delivered all at once.</p>
</div>`,
