    dek: `Documentaries and niche films sell internationally on different terms than genre features — through different buyers, channels, and appeal. A documentary film sales agent works a distinct landscape, and knowing it helps non-fiction and niche films find their global audience.`,
    body: `<p>Everything so far has largely assumed a narrative feature, but documentaries and niche films play the international-sales game on notably different terms — and if you've made one, it's worth understanding those differences, because <strong>docs and niche films sell abroad through different buyers, channels, and kinds of appeal than a genre feature.</strong> A documentary's international value often comes from broadcasters and specialized platforms as much as theatrical distributors, and its appeal travels on the strength of its subject rather than its genre hook — a doc on a globally resonant topic can sell into territories that a niche narrative never would. A documentary film sales agent (or an agent who handles non-fiction) works this distinct landscape, knowing which broadcasters and buyers in each territory acquire docs and how non-fiction deals are structured. The same is true for other niche films: a specialized subject or form finds its buyers in specialized corners of the international market. This chapter, opening Module 3, is about how docs and niche films find their global audience on their own terms.</p>

<h2>How docs and niche films sell abroad</h2>

<p>What's different about non-fiction and niche international sales:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Broadcasters matter more.</b> Documentaries often sell to television broadcasters and specialized channels in each territory, not just theatrical distributors — a different buyer landscape.</li>
  <li><b>Subject drives appeal.</b> A doc travels on the global resonance of its subject; a topic that matters worldwide can sell into territories a niche narrative couldn't reach.</li>
  <li><b>Specialized agents and buyers.</b> Non-fiction and niche films are served by agents and buyers who focus on those areas — fit with a doc-savvy agent matters.</li>
  <li><b>Different markets and events.</b> Documentaries have their own festivals, markets, and pitching forums where non-fiction deals and financing come together.</li>
  <li><b>Platforms and educational channels.</b> Docs and niche films may find international value through streaming, educational, and institutional channels beyond standard distribution.</li>
  <li><b>Modest but real.</b> Doc and niche international deals are often modest per territory, but a subject with global reach can sell widely and add up.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Finding the audience for non-fiction and niche films</h2>

<p>The essential insight is that <strong>documentaries and niche films should be sold internationally through the channels and agents that actually serve them — not through the generic genre-feature path.</strong> A documentary's international buyers are often broadcasters and specialized platforms rather than theatrical distributors, so a doc's foreign sales landscape looks different: instead of licensing to a local theatrical distributor in each territory, you may be licensing to a television broadcaster or a specialized channel that acquires documentaries for its audience. This means the right sales agent for a documentary is one who knows the non-fiction world — which broadcasters in which territories buy docs, how those deals are structured, and which documentary markets and forums to work — because a genre-focused agent may have little idea how to sell your film. The same logic extends to niche films of any kind: a film with a specialized subject, form, or audience finds its international buyers in the specialized corners of the market that care about exactly that, so matching your film to an agent and channels attuned to its niche is what makes international sales possible. A few honest points. First, <em>subject is the doc's passport</em> — a documentary on a subject of genuine global interest can travel remarkably well, selling into many territories on the strength of the topic, while a doc on a hyper-local subject may travel little, so an honest read of your subject's international resonance shapes expectations (much as genre appeal does for narratives). Second, <em>docs have their own ecosystem</em> — documentary festivals, markets, and pitching forums exist precisely to connect non-fiction filmmakers with international broadcasters and financiers, and plugging into that ecosystem (often earlier than a narrative would, sometimes at the financing stage) is central to a doc's international life. Third, <em>the money is usually modest but the reach can be wide</em> — individual doc and niche territory deals tend to be smaller than genre-feature deals, but a doc with global subject appeal can sell into a wide range of territories and broadcasters, so the accumulated total across many modest deals can still be meaningful. Fourth, <em>niche is a strength, not a limitation</em> — a film's specialized subject or audience, far from being a barrier to international sales, is often the very thing that lets it find dedicated buyers abroad who want exactly that, so leaning into your film's niche and matching it to the right specialized channels is the path, not a fallback. Documentaries and niche films aren't shut out of international sales — they simply reach the world through their own doors: specialized agents, broadcasters and platforms, dedicated markets and forums, and appeal built on subject and niche rather than genre. Match your non-fiction or niche film to the channels that serve it, and its global audience is reachable. Next, we look at another distinct case: the international sales of short films.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Documentaries and niche films aren't shut out of international sales — they reach the world through their own doors: specialized agents, broadcasters and platforms, dedicated markets, and appeal built on subject rather than genre.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>A friend made a documentary and tried to sell it internationally through a sales agent who mostly handled genre features. It went nowhere — not because the doc was weak, but because the agent didn't know the non-fiction world, the broadcasters who buy docs, or the documentary markets where those deals happen. When the film moved to an agent who lived and breathed non-fiction, it started selling to broadcasters in territory after territory, on the strength of a subject that resonated globally. The film hadn't changed. The match had. That's when I understood: for a doc, the right specialized agent and channels aren't a detail — they're the whole game.</p>
</div>`,
