    body: `<p>Short films occupy a special place in international sales, and it's important to set expectations honestly: <strong>shorts rarely command the territory-by-territory sales-agent treatment that features do, and their international value comes more from exposure, broadcasters, and platforms than from big licensing deals.</strong> A dedicated short film sales agent working a short across dozens of territories is a rare thing, because the economics that make a feature worth an agent's effort mostly don't apply to a short. That doesn't mean shorts have no international life — many shorts travel the world through festivals, sell to broadcasters and specialized short-film platforms, and build their maker's international profile — but the shape of a short's global journey is different from a feature's. If you've made a short and are wondering about international sales, this chapter gives you a realistic picture: what's achievable, where a short's value actually lies, and how to pursue it without chasing a feature-style campaign that shorts rarely support.</p>

<h2>How shorts travel internationally</h2>

<p>The realities of short-film international life:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Festivals are the main international stage.</b> Shorts travel the world primarily through festivals — international exposure and profile, more than direct sales, is the core value.</li>
  <li><b>Dedicated short sales agents are rare.</b> Few agents work shorts territory by territory the way they do features — the economics usually don't support it.</li>
  <li><b>Broadcasters and platforms buy shorts.</b> Some TV broadcasters and specialized short-film platforms license shorts, offering modest but real international revenue.</li>
  <li><b>Distributors and aggregators exist for shorts.</b> Certain companies specialize in placing shorts with international outlets — a realistic channel where a full agent isn't.</li>
  <li><b>Value is often indirect.</b> A short's biggest international payoff is frequently the profile, relationships, and career momentum it builds, which feed your next (feature) project.</li>
  <li><b>Keep expectations honest.</b> Direct international revenue from a short is usually modest — pursue it, but treat exposure and career-building as the main prize.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Pursuing a short's international life well</h2>

<p>The right approach to a short's international sales is to <strong>lead with festivals and exposure, use the realistic sales channels that exist for shorts, and treat profile-building as the primary return.</strong> A short's international journey runs mainly through festivals, where it can screen around the world, win recognition, and build your profile as a filmmaker — and that exposure is genuinely valuable, often more so than any direct revenue, because it's what opens doors for your next project and builds the international relationships that matter over a career. Alongside the festival run, there are realistic sales channels for shorts: some broadcasters and specialized short-film platforms license shorts for modest fees, and certain short-film distributors or aggregators specialize in placing shorts with international outlets, so a short isn't entirely shut out of revenue — it just reaches it through these channels rather than a feature-style territory campaign. The key is to pursue these opportunities without over-investing in a full sales-agent hunt that shorts rarely support, and to keep your expectations honest about the modest direct revenue involved. A few honest points. First, <em>exposure is the real currency for shorts</em> — the international profile a short builds through a strong festival run is usually its most valuable outcome, feeding your reputation, relationships, and the prospects of your next film, so treating profile as the main prize (rather than direct sales) leads to better decisions. Second, <em>realistic channels exist, so use them</em> — broadcasters, short-film platforms, and short-focused distributors/aggregators do license shorts internationally, and pursuing these is worthwhile for the modest revenue and reach they offer, as long as you don't expect feature-scale returns. Third, <em>a short can be a calling card, not just a product</em> — many filmmakers use a well-traveled short specifically to attract attention to a feature project or to themselves as a director, so thinking of your short's international life as career strategy (not just sales) unlocks its real value. Fourth, <em>don't over-invest relative to the return</em> — because a short's direct international revenue is usually modest, the effort you put into chasing it should be proportionate, favoring the high-value festival exposure and the easy, realistic sales channels over a disproportionate, feature-style campaign. Short films travel the world, but on their own terms: through festivals and exposure first, realistic broadcaster and platform channels second, and profile-building as the true return. Approach your short's international life with those honest priorities, and you'll get real value from it — much of it the kind that pays off in your next project. Next, we bring the choosing question to a head: how to choose the right sales agent for your film.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A short's biggest international payoff is usually the profile it builds, not the fees it earns. Lead with festivals and exposure, use the realistic channels that exist, and treat career-building as the true return.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I spent a while trying to sell an early short internationally the way I'd sell a feature — hunting for a sales agent to work it territory by territory. It was the wrong model; almost no agent works shorts that way, and I wasted energy. What actually paid off was the festival run: the short traveled to festivals around the world, built my profile, and led directly to the relationships and attention that got my first feature going. A couple of broadcaster and platform licenses brought in modest money along the way. The real return wasn't revenue — it was the career door the short's international exposure opened. I stopped selling my short like a feature and started using it like a calling card.</p>
</div>`,
