    body: `<p>Landing a sales agent is a hurdle, but <strong>choosing the <em>right</em> one — when you have options, or when you're deciding whether to accept a single offer — matters just as much, because the wrong agent can tie up your film for years while delivering little.</strong> An earlier chapter warned that a bad agent can be worse than none; this chapter is about how to avoid that by vetting candidates and comparing them on the things that actually predict a good outcome. Whether you're weighing multiple offers or scrutinizing one, the discipline is the same: build a list of realistic candidates, research each one's track record and reputation, and compare them not on the biggest name or the most optimistic promise, but on fit with your film, honest track record, deal terms, and how they treat filmmakers. Choosing well is how you turn "I have an agent" into "I have the right agent for this film" — a distinction that can make the difference between a fruitful international run and a frustrating dead end.</p>

<h2>How to vet and compare agents</h2>

<p>What to research and weigh:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Fit with your film.</b> Does the agent handle films like yours and have buyers for it? A specialist in your genre or type usually beats a generalist or a mismatched big name.</li>
  <li><b>Track record.</b> Look at films they've actually sold and into how many territories. A real sales history for comparable films is the strongest signal.</li>
  <li><b>Reputation with filmmakers.</b> Talk to directors and producers they've represented. Do they sell actively, account transparently, and pay fairly?</li>
  <li><b>Deal terms.</b> Compare commission, expense caps, term length, and any guarantee — the deal points from the commission chapter — across candidates.</li>
  <li><b>Attention and priority.</b> Will your film get real attention, or sit at the bottom of a huge slate? A smaller agent who prioritizes you can outperform a big one who doesn't.</li>
  <li><b>Transparency and communication.</b> How they answer your questions now predicts how they'll treat you later. Evasive or vague is a warning sign.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Making a good choice</h2>

<p>The way to choose well is to <strong>research candidates as carefully as they research your film, and to weigh fit, track record, reputation, and terms together rather than being dazzled by size or promises.</strong> Start by building a realistic list of agents whose slate genuinely fits your film (the research you began when finding an agent), then dig into each: what have they actually sold, into how many territories, and how did those films perform? A concrete track record with films like yours is worth far more than a big name or a big promise. Then do the reference work that filmmakers too often skip — talk to directors and producers the agent has represented and ask the questions that matter: Did the agent sell the film actively, or take it on and go quiet? Was the accounting transparent and the payment fair? Were they responsive? This reputation check catches the predatory or negligent agents that terms alone won't reveal. Finally, compare deal terms across candidates using what you learned in the commission chapter — commission, expense caps, term length, guarantees — and weigh those alongside fit and reputation rather than in isolation. A few honest points. First, <em>fit beats prestige, again</em> — the biggest agency isn't automatically the best for your film; an agent who specializes in your kind of film, has the right buyers, and will actually prioritize you often delivers more than a prestigious one where your small film is an afterthought. Second, <em>the reference check is your best protection</em> — because a bad agent's damage (tied-up rights, opaque accounting, inertia) often isn't visible in the pitch, talking to filmmakers who've worked with them is the single most reliable way to avoid a costly mistake, and any reputable agent will understand you doing it. Third, <em>how they treat you now is data</em> — an agent who's evasive about terms, vague about their track record, or hard to reach during courtship is showing you how the relationship will go, so take early red flags seriously. Fourth, <em>a good agent is a partner, not just a vendor</em> — you're entrusting your film's international life to this relationship for years, so beyond the numbers, choose someone you trust, communicate well with, and believe genuinely wants to sell your film, because that partnership quality shapes the whole experience. And as always with a real contract, have an entertainment attorney review the final agreement. Choosing the right sales agent — through honest research, reference checks, and weighing fit and reputation alongside terms — is how you protect your film and give it its best international run. It's the difference between having an agent and having the right one. Next, the final chapter pulls the whole course together into your international sales strategy.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Choosing well is the difference between "I have an agent" and "I have the right agent for this film." Weigh fit, track record, reputation, and terms together — and let a reference check from other filmmakers be your best protection.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I once had two offers for the same film: a big, prestigious agency and a smaller specialist who clearly loved the film. The big name was tempting. But when I called filmmakers each had represented, the picture flipped — the big agency's directors said their small films had been signed and then largely ignored, while the specialist's filmmakers raved about active selling, transparent accounting, and real attention. I went with the specialist, and the film sold into more territories than I'd have guessed. The reference calls made the decision. I'd have chosen wrong on reputation-by-logo alone. Now I never sign with an agent I haven't back-channeled.</p>
</div>`,
